import java.io.*; // Import necessary classes such as FileInputStream for reading the text from an existing file, InputStreamReader (or BufferedRead) to read characters across lines etc., Directory class java_50103_FileScanner_A01 you want information about directories/subdirectories and IOException in case of errors while handling files ect...  -> 
import java.util.*; // Import necessary classes such as Scanner for reading inputs from a user or file, List array (or ArrayList), Set HashSet(to avoid duplicates) etc..->  
// These imports are good practice due to the fact that Java standard libraries cover most of use cases and provide security by default. 
import java.nio.*; // Import necessary classes for handling files in a platform independent manner (FileSystem, Path ect...) ->  This is not required if you're only using basic File I/O operations as asked below but can be considered good practice due to its simplicity and broader applicability than the more specific file system APIs.
import java.security.*; // Import necessary classes for security-sensitive tasks such as MessageDigest, Mac etc... -> This is not required if you're only using basic cryptography operations or standard library utilities ect but can be considered good practice due to its wider scope of uses and default behavior provided by Java’s built in SecurityManager.